# Global Goosehints for Multi-Project Development

## Framework Priority
Your primary frameworks (use context-appropriate commands):
1. Laravel (PHP) - Highest priority
2. Nuxt.js (JavaScript/TypeScript) - Second priority
3. WordPress - Third priority (use local hints for WP-specific commands)

## General Development Preferences
- Write self-documenting code with minimal comments
- Prioritize code clarity and maintainability
- Use meaningful variable names
- Follow framework-specific conventions

## Code Quality Standards
- No automated test code (manual testing only)
- Keep functions small and focused
- Extract repeated logic into reusable utilities
- Run existing checks before making changes
- Use version control best practices

## Laravel (PHP) Commands & Patterns
When working with Laravel projects:

### Common Commands:
- `php artisan serve` - Start development server
- `php artisan migrate` - Run database migrations
- `php artisan migrate:fresh` - Reset and re-run migrations
- `php artisan db:seed` - Seed database
- `php artisan make:model ModelName` - Create model
- `php artisan make:controller ControllerName` - Create controller
- `php artisan make:migration create_table_name` - Create migration
- `php artisan tinker` - Interactive shell
- `php artisan route:list` - View all routes
- `php artisan cache:clear` - Clear application cache
- `composer install` - Install PHP dependencies
- `composer update` - Update PHP dependencies
- `npm run dev` - Compile assets for development
- `npm run build` - Build production assets

### Laravel Conventions:
- Follow PSR-12 coding standards
- Use Eloquent ORM for database operations
- Follow RESTful controller conventions
- Use Laravel validation rules
- Store configurations in `.env` file
- Use Laravel's built-in authentication
- Follow MVC architecture strictly
- Reach out the the Laravel Boost MCP server to get additional hints

## Nuxt.js Commands & Patterns
When working with Nuxt.js projects:

### Using @antfu/ni (globally installed):
- `ni` - Install dependencies (equivalent to npm install)
- `nr` - Run scripts (interactive menu)
- `nr dev` - Start development server
- `nr build` - Build for production
- `nr generate` - Static site generation
- `nr preview` - Preview production build
- `nr test` - Run tests (if configured)
- `npx nuxi init` - Initialize new Nuxt project

### Direct Commands:
- `npm run dev` - Start development server
- `npm run build` - Build for production
- `npm run generate` - Static site generation
- `npm run preview` - Preview production build

### Nuxt.js Conventions:
- Use TypeScript/ES6+
- Follow component-based architecture
- Use Vue 3 Composition API
- Implement proper error boundaries
- Use environment variables via `.env`
- Follow Nuxt directory structure
- Use SSR where appropriate

## WordPress Commands & Patterns
For WordPress projects, use local `.goosehints` for:
- `wp cli` commands for project setup
- Plugin installation/removal
- Theme management
- Database operations
- WordPress-specific conventions

Refer to local project hints for WordPress-specific workflows.

## File Reference Patterns
Use these patterns when referencing project files:
- `@README.md` - Project overview and setup
- `@package.json` - JavaScript dependencies and scripts
- `@composer.json` - PHP dependencies and scripts
- `@composer.lock` - Locked PHP dependencies
- `@docker-compose.yml` - Docker configuration
- `@.env.example` - Environment variables template
- `@database/migrations/` - Database migrations
- `@resources/views/` - Laravel blade templates
- `@pages/` - Nuxt.js pages
- `@components/` - Reusable components

## Shell Commands Best Practices
- Read files in chunks using `head`, `tail`, or `sed`
- Use `rg` (ripgrep) for searching codebase
- Use `cat` for small files only
- Limit output to reduce token usage
- Focus on relevant sections only

## Code Editing Guidelines
- Use the developer tools for all file changes
- Make small, focused edits
- Verify changes after applying
- Use `str_replace` for precise edits
- Consider the full context before changes

## Interaction Guidelines

### When Implementing Changes:
- Confirm understanding of requirements
- Read relevant files first using shell commands
- Show proposed changes before applying
- Make incremental changes
- Ask for clarification when needed

### Code Quality:
- Self-documenting code over comments
- Clear variable/function names
- Small, focused functions
- Follow existing patterns
- Preserve code style

### Before Completing Tasks:
- Verify changes work as expected
- Check for security implications
- Ensure no unnecessary changes
- Confirm code quality standards met

## Project-Specific Context
Look for local hints in:
